<p><b>Mortimer Jerome Adler</b> (<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1902-12-28"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="12-28"><a href="/wiki/December_28" title="December 28">December 28</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1902" title="1902">1902</a></span> – <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2001-06-28"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="06-28"><a href="/wiki/June_28" title="June 28">June 28</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/2001" title="2001">2001</a></span>) was an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> educator, philosopher, and popular author. As a philosopher he worked with <a href="/wiki/Aristotelian" title="Aristotelian">Aristotelian</a> and <a href="/wiki/Thomistic" title="Thomistic" class="mw-redirect">Thomistic</a> thought. He lived for the longest stretches in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>, <a href="/wiki/Chicago" title="Chicago">Chicago</a>, <a href="/wiki/San_Francisco" title="San Francisco">San Francisco</a>, and <a href="/wiki/San_Mateo" title="San Mateo">San Mateo</a>. He worked for <a href="/wiki/Columbia_University" title="Columbia University">Columbia University</a>, the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Chicago" title="University of Chicago">University of Chicago</a>, <a href="/wiki/Encyclop%C3%A6dia_Britannica" title="Encyclopædia Britannica">Encyclopædia Britannica</a>, and Adler's own Institute for Philosophical Research. Adler was married twice and had four children.<sup id="cite_ref-NYT_Obit_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NYT_Obit-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Angelicum_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Angelicum-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
